05524nam a22012135i 9781400833788DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212009nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008337887 a10.1515/97814008337882doi  a(DE-B1597)588950  a(OCoLC)1262308008  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a276.2/012221 aBagnall, Roger S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEarly Christian Books in Egypt /cRoger S. Bagnall. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (128 p.) :b15 halftones. 11 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tPreface -- tA Note on Abbreviations -- tChapter I The Dating of the Earliest Christian Books in Egypt -- tChapter II Two Case Studies -- tChapter III The Economics of Book Production -- tChapter IV The Spread of the Codex -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Papyrological Texts Discussed0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the past hundred years, much has been written about the early editions of Christian texts discovered in the region that was once Roman Egypt. Scholars have cited these papyrus manuscripts--containing the Bible and other Christian works--as evidence of Christianity's presence in that historic area during the first three centuries AD. In Early Christian Books in Egypt, distinguished papyrologist Roger Bagnall shows that a great deal of this discussion and scholarship has been misdirected, biased, and at odds with the realities of the ancient world. Providing a detailed picture of the social, economic, and intellectual climate in which these manuscripts were written and circulated, he reveals that the number of Christian books from this period is likely fewer than previously believed.Bagnall explains why papyrus manuscripts have routinely been dated too early, how the role of Christians in the history of the codex has been misrepresented, and how the place of books in ancient society has been misunderstood. The author offers a realistic reappraisal of the number of Christians in Egypt during early Christianity, and provides a thorough picture of the economics of book production during the period in order to determine the number of Christian papyri likely to have existed. Supporting a more conservative approach to dating surviving papyri, Bagnall examines the dramatic consequences of these findings for the historical understanding of the Christian church in Egypt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAntinoopolis papyrus.  aAntoninus Pius.  aApamea (Syria), church of.  aApocalypse of John.  aArian controversy.  aArsinoe (city).  aBilabel, Friedrich.  aBonner, Campbell.  aCallimachus.  aCassiodorus.  aCharlesworth, Scott.  aChristianity, Egyptian.  aChristianity.  aChurch History (Eusebius).  aCoptic marginal glosses.  aCyrenaica.  aDecius, emperor.  aDemotic.  aEgyptians, hellenized.  aEusebius.  aFayyum papyri.  aGascou, Jean.  aGiessen papyrus.  aGnosticism and Gnostics.  aGospel of Thomas.  aHadrian.  aHermopolis.  aHipponon.  aJakab, Attila.  aJesus Seminar.  aKenyon, Frederic.  aLollianus.  aManichaeism.  aMenander.  aNew Testament.  aOxyrhynchus.  aPanopolis.  aPhilodemus.  aPoseidippos.  aSchmelz, Georg.  aStark, Rodney.  aTorah.  aTrajan.  aTurner, Eric.  aWachtel, Klaus.  aWilliams, Megan.  aWipszycka, Ewa.  abook rolls.  acodex/codices.  apapyri.  avan Minnen, Peter.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400833788zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www